Data Summary Figures

Then, we can calculate the mean, median, SE, SD for further exploration.

#calculate the mean, median, SE, sd, etc.:
II_Summary <- II_Data %>%
  group_by(Temperature,Age) %>%
  summarise(mean_CFUs = mean(CFUs),
            median_CFUs = median(CFUs),
            sd_CFUs = sd(CFUs),
            n_CFUs = n(),
            SE_CFUs = sd(CFUs)/sqrt(n()))

Preliminary Data Analysis and Model Fitting

What is the distribution of the data? Are there any correlations? What can we determine from assessing the variance, etc.?

We are not log-transforming the data because of the zero values at 27C, but we don’t want to exclude this data either.

Common models for count data include the negative binomial regression, zero-inflated regression, and Poisson regression.

Helpful resources:

Delignette-Muller, M. L., & Dutang, C. (2015). fitdistrplus: An R Package for Fitting Distributions. Journal of Statistical Software, 64(4), 1–34. Alexander, N., 2012. Review: analysis of parasite and other skewed counts. Tropical Medicine & International Health 17, 684–693.. doi:10.1111/j.1365-3156.2012.02987.x https://doi.org/10.18637/jss.v064.i04 https://data.princeton.edu/wws509/r/overdispersion https://fukamilab.github.io/BIO202/04-C-zero-data.html https://stats.oarc.ucla.edu/r/dae/negative-binomial-regression/ https://www.jstatsoft.org/article/view/v027i08

#descriptive statistics of the data and graph
descdist(II_Data$CFUs, boot = 1000)

## summary statistics
## ------
## min:  0   max:  3984000 
## median:  180500 
## mean:  681923.5 
## estimated sd:  906744.2 
## estimated skewness:  1.431304 
## estimated kurtosis:  4.26786

We are estimating skewness and kurtosis, using bootstrap samples. This is constructed by random sampling with replacement from original data set. There is high variance regardless of bootstrapping.

How does the variance compare to the mean of the CFU data?

#check mean and variance of CFU data
ggplot(II_Data, aes(x=CFUs)) + 
  geom_histogram(bins = 100)

r <- c(mean(II_Data$CFUs), var(II_Data$CFUs))
c(mean=r[1],var=r[2],ratio=r[2]/r[1]) #ratio is 1.2e6 (greater than 1.1 and considered large / overdispersed)
##         mean          var        ratio 
## 6.819235e+05 8.221851e+11 1.205685e+06

Poisson assumption of equal mean and variance does not hold true. The variance is greater than the mean (ratio = 1.2e6) and is considered over-dispersed.

This suggests a Neg Binom model may be better (mean does not equal variance, which is assumed by Poisson dist).

First, we’ll look at the Poisson dist and Neg Bin dist.

#assess fits:
#check to see if the data follow a poisson distribution
fit_poisson_CFUs <- fitdist((II_Data$CFUs),"pois")
summary(fit_poisson_CFUs)
## Fitting of the distribution ' pois ' by maximum likelihood 
## Parameters : 
##        estimate Std. Error
## lambda 681923.5         NA
## Loglikelihood:  -381063613   AIC:  762127229   BIC:  762127233
plot(fit_poisson_CFUs)

#check to see if the data follow a negative binomial distribution
fit_negbinom_CFUs <- fitdist((II_Data$CFUs), "nbinom")
summary(fit_negbinom_CFUs)
## Fitting of the distribution ' nbinom ' by maximum likelihood 
## Parameters : 
##          estimate Std. Error
## size 3.420331e-01         NA
## mu   6.822661e+05         NA
## Loglikelihood:  -9629.12   AIC:  19262.24   BIC:  19271.33 
## Correlation matrix:
## [1] NA
plot(fit_negbinom_CFUs)

#compare the two fits:

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
#graphics.off()
plot.legend <- c("pois", "nbinom")
denscomp(list(fit_poisson_CFUs,fit_negbinom_CFUs),legendtext = plot.legend)

It looks like the negative binomial model over-corrects for the overdisperison and that it does not properly account for the excess zero CFU values.

Fitting a Zero-Inflated Negative Binomial Distribution

We can try fitting a zero-inflated poisson or negative binomial model instead. This is a two part model that predicts (1) the probability of having a zero or not (binomial, log link) and (2) the estimate when it is not zero (poisson or negative binomial, log link).

Helpful resources: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5628625/#:~:text=Structural%20zeros%20refer%20to%20zero,zero%20due%20to%20sampling%20variability. https://lanzaroark.org/docs/zero.pdf https://www.jstatsoft.org/article/view/v027i08 https://m-clark.github.io/models-by-example/hurdle.html https://search.r-project.org/CRAN/refmans/pscl/html/hurdle.html https://data.library.virginia.edu/getting-started-with-hurdle-models/ https://www.r-bloggers.com/2013/05/veterinary-epidemiologic-research-count-and-rate-data-zero-counts/ https://stats.oarc.ucla.edu/r/dae/negative-binomial-regression/ https://stats.oarc.ucla.edu/r/dae/zinb/

Using the zero-inflated negative binomial model, we can predict what the expected CFU counts would be for each temperature-age combination, and we can compare these values to the observed values. We can also identify how the zero-inflation component affects the expected CFU count.

#create data frame for predictions:
newdata1 <- expand.grid(c(-2.76,0.24,2.24),rep(c(-6.3,-2.3,2.7,7.7)))
#newdata1 <- expand.grid(c(27,30,32), rep(c(1,5,10,15)))
colnames(newdata1) <- c("Temperature", "Age")

#what can we predict with the model? 

#we can predict the response with and without a zero-inflation component, the probability of the CFU observation, probability of an excess zero

newdata1$count <- predict(z3, newdata1, type="count") #predicted response w/o zero inflation
newdata1$response <- predict(z3, newdata1, type="response") #predicted response (numerical) w/ zero inflation
newdata1$excesszeroprob <- predict(z3,newdata1,type="zero") #predicted predicted probabilities of zero component
newdata1$diffwzi <- (newdata1$count - newdata1$response) #this is the difference between the outcome with and without accounting for zero-inflation

Model Interpretation:

For the count model (non-zero), Temperature, Age, and the Temperature*Age Interaction are all significant predictors of the log(CFUs).

The interaction term is significant - this means that the individual coefficients for the main effects of temperature and age cannot be interpreted in the same way as they would be if no interaction were included in the model.

The estimates from the model, without transformation, are on the natural log scale and are additive (because it is a negative binomial model with a log link).

The estimate for temperature is 0.708936. This means that for each one unit increase in temperature, the expected change in log(CFUs) is 0.708936, when the age is at its average (~7 days) (and there is no interaction). The estimate for age is -0.556265. For each one unit increase in age, the expected change in log(CFUs) is 0.158466, when temperature is at its average (~29.7 degrees C) (and there is no interaction).

The coefficient for a one unit change in temperature only indicates an increase in log(CFUs) of 0.708936 when the value of age is at its average (due to centering) not when all variables are held constant - this is because you cannot hold both the value of main effects and the interaction term constant without changing one or the other (the interaction includes the main effect).

Temperature and age interact to increase the infection intensity (positive estimate of 0.024016).

Because the interaction term is significant, it is much more meaningful to interpret the interaction and the effects of temperature and age by looking at the marginal effects (see figures and calculations further below).

The coefficient for the interaction term indicates the additional change in the effect or slope of Temp for every unit change in Age (and vice versa).

The intercept of the count model indicates that the expected number of log(CFUs) is 12.6732, when temperature and age are held constant at their averages. Thus, when the temperature is 29.7C and the mosquito is 7 days old, the estimated number of CFUs is 319,079.

Theta equals the inverse of the dispersion parameter.

The significant p-value for the intercept for the zero-inflation model indicates that the intercept is non-zero. Therefore, the baseline odds of an excessive zero (zero inflation model) is exp(-3.4222)= 0.0326. This is an odds ratio because it is a binomial model with logit link.

We can take the estimates and back-transform them to identify how changes in temperature and age are expected to alter the CFUs (below).

#put these values into the following equation in the function f:
f <- function(data, i) {
  require(pscl)
  z3 <- zeroinfl(CFUs ~ Temperature*Age | 1,
                 dist = 'negbin',
                 data = data[i,],
                 start = list(count = c(12.6732, 0.7089, 0.1585,0.024), zero = c(-3.4222)))
  as.vector(t(do.call(rbind, coef(summary(z3)))[, 1:2]))
}

We can create risk and odds ratios because the parameter is the log of the ratio of expected counts (due to the distribution) (see https://stats.oarc.ucla.edu/r/dae/negative-binomial-regression/).

The exp(estimate) scale is multiplicative, but the estimate scale is additive because it is a negative binomial model.

The exponentiated estimate for the intercept tells us that when temp and age are at their average (~29.7C and 7 days old), the estimated number of CFUs per mosquito is 319,079.

With every increase in temperature (degree C), the number of CFUs is 2.03 times greater (more than doubles), given that age is held constant at the average (7 days). With every increase in age, the number of CFUs is 1.17 times greater (increases by almost 20%), given that temp is held constant at the average (29.7C). Temp and age interact significantly to increase infection intensity.

The baseline odds ratio for an excessive zero (cleared infection) is 0.03 (3%) when at 29.7C and 7 days old.

We can also better understand the interaction of temperature and age using interaction plots and estimated marginal means. The marginal means and effects can be reported (see tables for marginal means by temp and by age), and the visual graphs are a great representation of how temperature and age interact to change the CFU outcome. Looking at marginal means for interpreting the effects of temperature, age, and their interaction is more informative given the significant interaction of temperature and age on the expected count of CFUs.

  geom_ribbon(aes(ymax=UCL, ymin=LCL, fill=Temperature), alpha=0.3)+
  labs(x="Adult Age (days post eclosion)", y="CFUs", color="Temperature (˚C)", 
       fill="Temperature (˚C)",
       title="Interaction of temperaure and age on expected CFUs")

       title="Interaction of temperaure and age on expected CFUs")

Main messages:

  1. Temperature, Age, and their interaction significantly impact the infection intensity (expected log CFUs), with warmer temperatures and older ages interacting to increase the infection intensity. At warmer temperatures, older ages increase infection intensity more than at cooler temperatures, and vice versa.

  2. Because of the significant interaction, the marginal means are a better way to understand how temperature, age, and their interaction alter infection intensity.

  3. The count data were over-dispersed and zero-inflated, best modeled by a zero-inflated negative binomial distribution.
